03480nam a22004815i 9780773588660DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735886607 a10.1515/97807735886602doi  a(DE-B1597)654595  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPN2091S6bO93.2016 7aDRA0000002bisacsh04a792.02/42231 aOvadija, Mladen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDramaturgy of Sound in the Avant-garde and Postdramatic Theatre /cMladen Ovadija. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Performativity of Voice and Sound in Theatre -- tAvant-garde and Postmodern Conceptions of Aurality -- tSound Poetry and Bruitist Performance: Words-in-Freedom -- tZaum: From a “Beyonsense” Language to an Idiom of Theatre -- tThe Dramaturgy of Sound: From Futurist Serate to Sintesi -- tSound as Structure: Toward an Aural Architecture of Theatre -- tThe Avant-garde Dramaturgy of Sound -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSound is born and dies with action. In this surprising, resourceful study, Mladen Ovadija makes a case for the centrality of sound as an integral element of contemporary theatre. He argues that sound in theatre inevitably "betrays" the dramatic text, and that sound is performance. Until recently, theatrical sound has largely been regarded as supplemental to the dramatic plot. Now, however, sound is the subject of renewed interest in theatrical discourse. Dramaturgy of sound, Ovadija argues, reads and writes a theatrical idiom based on two inseparable, intertwined strands - the gestural, corporeal power of the performer’s voice and the structural value of stage sound. His extensive research in experimental performance and his examination of the pioneering work by Futurists, Dadaists, and Expressionists enable Ovadija to create a powerful study of autonomous sound as an essential element in the creation of synesthetic theatre. Dramaturgy of Sound in the Avant-garde and Postdramatic Theatre presents a cogent argument about a continuous tradition in experimental theatre running from early modernist to contemporary works.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAvant-garde (Aesthetics). 0aExperimental theaterxHistory and criticism. 0aTheatersxSound effects. 7aDRAMA / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358866040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773588660423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773588660/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles